      <!-- 5 · CANDLING -->
      <section id="candling">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">How do we prove an African Grey egg is fertile before it ships?</h2>
        <p>Candling is our proof of fertility, and we do it before an egg ever leaves the aviary: passing a bright light through the shell reveals the developing embryo, so "fertile" is something we've seen, not something we've asserted. On request we'll send you a dated candling photo or short video of your own clutch — the transparency the scam farms structurally can't provide.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "candling-african-grey-egg-fertility-stages.webp"} srcset={IMG + "candling-african-grey-egg-fertility-stages-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "candling-african-grey-egg-fertility-stages.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Candling an African Grey egg shows veins, air cell and embryo development by day" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">What does candling reveal by day 5, 10 and 18?</h3>
        <p>Candling tells a developmental story on a schedule: fine veins appear around day 5, a web of vessels and a defined air cell by day 10, and a dark embryo shadow by day 18. Reading those stages is how we confirm an egg is truly progressing before we pack it.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">Dated candling photo or video on request</h4>
        <p>Ask and we'll document it: a timestamped candling image or clip of your clutch, so your first fertility check happens before shipping, not after a loss. That single file resolves most egg-scam fear on its own, which is precisely why we offer it up front.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">Veins, air cell and embryo — what we look for</h5>
        <p>Under the light we're reading three things — branching blood vessels, a clean air cell at the blunt end, and embryo movement or shadow — and a clear "candle-through" egg with none of these is one we pull, not ship. Honest candling means some eggs don't make the cut.</p>

        <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note — Teri's candling routine</h6>
        <p>In Teri's words, she candles in a darkened room, blunt-end up, and re-checks anything ambiguous a few days later rather than guessing — patience beats optimism with a developing egg. It's the same careful eye she brings to every clutch we hatch here.</p>
      </section>

