      <!-- 9 · HEALTH -->
      <section id="health">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">What health screening and guarantee back our African Greys?</h2>
        <p>Health is where an ethical breeder earns trust, so every bird we place is PCR-screened and vet-checked before it leaves — and the eggs come from that same tested foundation. A reserved chick arrives with a written health guarantee; an egg, by its nature, cannot carry one, and we say so plainly rather than pretend otherwise.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "hand-feeding-african-grey-chick-formula.webp"} srcset={IMG + "hand-feeding-african-grey-chick-formula-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "hand-feeding-african-grey-chick-formula.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Hand-feeding a downy African Grey chick with formula at our aviary" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">What does every C.A.Gs bird leave with?</h3>
        <p>The document folder is the same across every companion bird we place, and it's exactly what a fake listing can't assemble. Here's the stack that travels with a reserved chick:</p>
        <div class="doc-stack" role="group" aria-label="Documents every C.A.Gs grey leaves with">
          <p class="ds-title">Every grey leaves with</p>
          <ol class="ds-list">
            <li><b>PBFD PCR screening</b><span>Psittacine Beak &amp; Feather Disease — negative required</span></li>
            <li><b>Avian Polyomavirus PCR</b><span>Second core psittacine screen, same lab standard</span></li>
            <li><b>DNA sexing certificate</b><span>Lab-confirmed male or female, in writing</span></li>
            <li><b>Avian-vet health certificate</b><span>Issued just before travel day</span></li>
            <li><b>Hatch certificate + closed band</b><span>Traceable to our aviary and clutch</span></li>
          </ol>
        </div>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">PBFD &amp; Polyomavirus PCR screening</h4>
        <p><a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Association of Avian Veterinarians</a> treats PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus as core screening for psittacines, so we PCR-test our breeding birds and chicks for both, with negatives required before placement, because those two diseases are the ones that quietly wreck a collection. Screening the parents is also why the fertile eggs come from a clean, tested line rather than an unknown one.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">The written health guarantee on reserved chicks</h5>
        <p>Reserved chicks carry a written health guarantee — full terms live on our <a href="/african-greys-for-sale-with-health-guarantee/">African Grey health guarantee page</a>. It covers the bird you can hold and vet-check; an egg's outcome depends on your incubator, which is the honest reason eggs are sold as-is to experienced breeders.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="seam"><img src={seam} width="150" height="50" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"></div>

      <!-- 10 · LEGAL -->
      <section id="legal">
        <h2 class="cag-h2">Are captive-bred African Grey eggs legal to buy in the USA?</h2>
        <p>Legality is a fair worry with African Greys, and the honest answer is reassuring: because our birds are captive-bred, their eggs are legal to own and transfer within the United States with the right paperwork. African Greys are CITES Appendix I, and we lean into that status rather than dodge it — it's the frame that separates documented breeders from the wild-caught trade we'll never touch.</p>
        <img class="sec-img inf-img" src={IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation.webp"} srcset={IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation-760.webp 760w, " + IMG + "captive-bred-cites-appendix-i-egg-documentation.webp 1408w"} sizes="(max-width:860px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" loading="lazy" decoding="async" alt="Captive-bred CITES Appendix I documentation accompanying African Grey eggs" />

        <h3 class="cag-h3">CITES Appendix I + USDA AWA, in plain English</h3>
        <p>In plain terms, CITES Appendix I is the strictest protection tier, and it makes captive-bred documentation essential — which is exactly why we keep it on every bird. Pair that with our USDA Animal Welfare Act license and you have a paper trail a fake listing simply cannot reproduce.</p>

        <h4 class="cag-h4">What paperwork travels with your birds</h4>
        <p>Documentation follows what we place: captive-bred CITES paperwork, DNA sexing certificates, an avian-vet health certificate, and a hatch certificate with a band number for our chicks. For a broader picture, <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">our CITES documentation guide</a> walks through each record.</p>

        <h5 class="cag-h5">Never wild-caught — captive-bred USA only</h5>
        <p><a href="https://www.parrots.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The World Parrot Trust</a> documents how responsible captive breeding relieves collection pressure on wild African Grey populations, and that ethic is absolute here: every egg and bird we sell is captive-bred in the USA, full stop — we have never dealt in wild-caught African Greys, and Appendix I is why that line holds.</p>

        <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation — CITES Appendix I history</h6>
        <p>The species moved up to <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES Appendix I</a> at CoP17 — effective January 2017, a tightening from its former Appendix II listing — per the Convention's own records. We reference the source so the status is verifiable, not just stated.</p>
      </section>

      <div class="seam"><img src={seam} width="150" height="50" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async"></div>

